This paper focuses on the role of network structure in social processes, specifically in online social networks. The paper discusses the development of quantitative measures to quantify a node's social context diversity in directed networks and investigates the role of social context diversity in predicting one's social reputation online. This topic is relevant to several sub-categories in computer science, including social networks (cs.SOC), information retrieval (cs.IR), and data structures (cs.DS). Additionally, the paper discusses the potential implications for collective intelligence and cybersecurity, which could fall under the categories of social computing (cs.SI) and cybersecurity (cs.CYBER).
